Zaragoza B]] in the fourth tier and [[Universidad de Las Palmas CF]] and [[CD Legan\u00e9s]] in the third. In January 2012, he signed with [[CD Tenerife]] in the latter league,<ref>[http://www.tenerifedeportivo.com/2012/01/04/aridane-el-tenerife-es-un-club-grande/ Aridane: \u201cEl Tenerife es un club grande\u201d (Aridane: \"Tenerife is a big club\")] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029212846/http://www.tenerifedeportivo.com/2012/01/04/aridane-el-tenerife-es-un-club-grande/|date=29 October 2013}}; Tenerife Deportivo, 4 January 2012 (in Spanish)</ref> scoring 25 goals in 37 games in [[2012\u201313 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his second season]] (adding two from three appearances in [[2013 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|the play-offs]]) to help the club return to the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]] after two years out.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.laopinion.es/deportes/2013/05/07/aridane-13-goleadores/473950.html|title=Aridane y 13 goleadores m\u00e1s|trans-title=Aridane and 13 other scorers|publisher=[[La Opini\u00f3n de Tenerife]]|language=Spanish|date=7 May 2013|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2013/06/16/seleccion/1371391424_048509.html El Alav\u00e9s aguanta con nueve y queda campe\u00f3n de Segunda B (Alav\u00e9s hold on with nine and are ''Segunda B'' champions)]; [[Diario AS]], 16 June 2013 (in Spanish)</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://eldia.es/deportes/2014-06-04/1-grancanario-Aridane-Santana-partido-cien-Tenerife.htm|title=El grancanario Aridane Santana, a un partido de los cien con el Tenerife|trans-title=Gran Canaria's Aridane Santana, one match from reaching one hundred with Tenerife|publisher=[[El D\u00eda (Canary Islands)|El D\u00eda]]|language=Spanish|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAridane played his first professional match on 1 September 2013, featuring the last 27 minutes of a 0\u20132 away loss to [[CD Mirand\u00e9s]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/09/01/futbol/2adivision/1378063714.html El Mirand\u00e9s quiso y pudo (Mirand\u00e9s wanted it and got it)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 1 September 2013 (in Spanish)</ref> He scored his first goal in the second division seven days later, in a 2\u20132 home draw against [[FC Barcelona B]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/2013/09/08/futbol/2adivision/1378667716.html Un entusiasta Tenerife no pudo pasar del empate ante el Bar\u00e7a B (Enthusiastic Tenerife could not earn more than a draw against Bar\u00e7a B)]; Marca, 8 September 2013 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nOn 6 July 2015, aged 28, Aridane terminated his contract with Tenerife and moved abroad for the first time in his career, after agreeing to a two-year deal with [[Bangkok Glass F.C.]] in Thailand.<ref>[http://www.goal.com/th/news/4280/%E0%B8%9F%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%A5%E0%B9%84%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%A2/2015/07/06/13351982/%E0%B8%AA%E0%B8%B7%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%87%E0%B9%82%E0%B8%AB%E0%B8%A1%E0%B8%AB%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%88%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%94%E0%B8%94%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%A5%E0%B8%AB%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A9%E0%B9%8C%E0%B8%AA%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%99?ICID=HP_TS_5 \u0e2a\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e17\u0e34\u0e07\u0e42\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01!\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e08\u0e35\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e14\u0e35\u0e25\u0e2b\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e22\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e19 (Bangkok Glass sign forward from Spanish giants)]; [[Goal (website)|Goal]], 6 July 2015 (in Thai)</ref> On 1 February of the following year he returned to his home country, signing a short-term deal with [[CD Mirand\u00e9s]] in the second division.<ref>[http://www.cdmirandes.com/noticia/aridane-santana-nuevo-jugador-del-c-d-mirandes Aridane Santana, nuevo jugador del C.D. Mirand\u00e9s (Aridane Santana, new player of C.D. Mirand\u00e9s)]; CD Mirand\u00e9s, 1 February 2016 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 2016, Aridane joined [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9]], [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|recently relegated to the third tier]].<ref>[http://www.albacetebalompie.es/aridane-santana-nuevo-jugador-del-alb/ Aridane Santana nuevo jugador del Alba (Aridane Santana new player of ''Alba'')] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917062651/http://www.albacetebalompie.es/aridane-santana-nuevo-jugador-del-alb/|date=17 September 2016}}; Albacete Balompi\u00e9, 3 August 2016 (in Spanish)</ref> In [[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his first season]] in [[Castilla-La Mancha]], he contributed 17 goals in 42 matches as his team were promoted as champions,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2017/05/24/mas_futbol/1495629550_626686.html|title=El gol en el Albacete tiene conexi\u00f3n canaria|trans-title=Goal at Albacete has a Canarian connection|publisher=Diario AS|first=Juan Manuel|last=Sevilla|language=Spanish|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref> including the extra time winner in the [[2017 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|play-off]] semi-final against [[CD Atl\u00e9tico Baleares]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.es/espana/castilla-la-mancha/abci-albacete-llega-final-para-ascenso-tras-dramatica-prorroga-201706111912_noticia.html|title=2\u20131: El Albacete llega a la final para el ascenso tras una dram\u00e1tica pr\u00f3rroga|trans-title=2\u20131: Albacete arrive in the promotion final after dramatic extra time|publisher=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|100288|Aridane}}\n*{{LaPreferente|73674|Aridane}}\n*{{Soccerway|aridane-jesus-santana-cabrera/61673|Aridane}}\n\n{{Odisha FC squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aridane Santana}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gran Canaria]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Canarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Fabril players]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza B players]]\n[[Category:Universidad de Las Palmas CF footballers]]\n[[Category:CD Legan\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:CD Tenerife players]]\n[[Category:CD Mirand\u00e9s footballers]]\n[[Category:Albacete Balompi\u00e9 players]]\n[[Category:Cultural Leonesa footballers]]\n[[Category:Thai League 1 players]]\n[[Category:BG Pathum United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League players]]\n[[Category:Odisha FC players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor tidyups overall, nothing hurt whatsoever.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aridane_Santana"}
{"title_page": "List of massacres in China", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}The following is a list of [[massacre]]s that have occurred in China. The massacres are grouped for different periods. \n\n== Imperial China (before 1912) ==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n|-\n! style=\"width:120px;\" |Name\n! style=\"width:65px;\" |Date\n! style=\"width:120px;\" |Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\" |Deaths\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n|[[Guangzhou massacre]]\n|878\u2013879\n|[[Guangzhou]]\n|{{ntsh|120000}}120,000\n|Foreign merchants ([[Muslim]] [[Arabs]], Muslim [[Persian people|Persians]], [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] Persians, [[Christians]], and [[Jews]]) were killed. {{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n|-\n|Sichuan massacre\n|1645-1646\n|[[Sichuan]], China\n|{{ntsh|1,000,000}}1,000,000 est.<ref name=\"parsons\" />\n|There is no reliable figure, but estimated 1 million out of 3 million [[Sichuanese people|Sichuanese]] were massacred mainly by the army of [[Zhang Xianzhong]].<ref name=\"parsons\">{{cite journal |author=James B. Parsons |date=May 1957 |title=The Culmination of a Chinese Peasant Rebellion: Chang Hsien-chung in Szechwan, 1644-46 |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?aid=7001496 |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |publisher=Association for Asian Studies |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=387\u2013400 |doi=10.2307/2941233 |jstor=2941233}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Yangzhou massacre]]\n|1645\n|[[Yangzhou]]\n|{{ntsh|299999}}=?< 300,000 (modern estimate)<ref>Struve (1993) (note at p. 269), following a 1964 article by Zhang Defang, notes that the entire city's population at the time was not likely to be more than 300,000, and that of the entire Yangzhou Prefecture, 800,000.</ref>\n|\n|-\n|[[Dzungar genocide]]\n|1755\u20131757\n|[[Dzungar Khanate]]\n|{{ntsh|540000}}540,000<ref>Geometric mean of 480 and 600 thousand rounded up to nearest ten thousand.</ref>\n|480,000 to 600,000 deaths. 80% of population killed {{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n|-\n|[[Ningpo Massacre]]\n|1800s\n|[[Ningbo]]\n|{{ntsh|40}}40\n|Cantonese pirates supported by the Qing massacred 40 Portuguese pirates.\n|-\n|[[Jindandao incident]]\n|1891\n|[[Inner Mongolia]]\n|{{ntsh|150,000}}150,000 - 500,000\n|Ethnic tensions led a Chinese secret society, Jindandao, to revolt and kill 150,000 - 500,000 Mongols.\n|-\n|[[Port Arthur massacre (China)|Port Arthur massacre]]\n|1894, November 21\n|[[L\u00fcshunkou]], [[Liaoning]]\n|{{ntsh|4500}}4500\n|1000\u201320,000{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n|-\n|[[Kucheng Massacre]]\n|1895, August 1\n|[[Gutian County|Gutian]], [[Fujian]]\n|{{ntsh|11}}11\n|11 British Missionaries killed by a fasting folk religious group on August 1, 1895\n|-\n|[[Taiyuan Massacre]]\n|1900, July\n|[[Taiyuan]], [[Shanxi]]\n|{{ntsh|45}} 45\n|\n|}\n\n== Republic of China (1912\u20131949) ==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Shanghai massacre of 1927]]\n|1927, April 12\n|[[Shanghai]]\n|{{ntsh|1200}}1200\n|300\u2013400 direct deaths. 5000 missing\n|-\n|[[Anti-communist mass killings#China|Kuomintang Anti-Communist massacre]]\n|1928\n|Nationwide in [[China]]\n|{{ntsh|300000}}300,000<ref name=\"Barnouin38\">Barnouin, Barbara and Yu Changgen. ''Zhou Enlai: A Political Life.'' Hong Kong: Chinese University of Hong Kong, 2006. {{ISBN|962-996-280-2}}.  Retrieved at <https://books.google.com/books?id=NztlWQeXf2IC&printsec=frontcover&dq=zhou+enlai&hl=en&ei=wBkuTdKyB4H_8AaJucigAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false> on March 12, 2011.  p.38</ref>\n|Mass executions of both alleged and actual [[communist]]s by the nationalist [[Kuomintang]].\n|-\n|Communist purge in [[Jiangxi\u2013Fujian Soviet]]\n|1931-1935\n|Most parts of [[Ganzhou]] and every part of [[Tingzhou fu|Tingzhou]]\n|{{ntsh|700000}}700,000<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L_bQX73aOvcC&pg=PA133|title=Mao: The Unknown Story|page=133}}</ref>\n|Occurred in the mountainous parts which are almost entirely only populated by Hakkas of Jiangxi and Fujian.\n|-\n||[[Kizil massacre]]\n|1933, June\n|near [[Kashgar]], [[Xinjiang]]\n|{{ntsh|800}}800\n|\n|-\n||[[Battle of Kashgar (1934)|Kashgar massacre]]\n|1934\n|[[Kashgar]], [[Xinjiang]]\n|{{ntsh|4000}}2,000-8,000\n|\n|-\n|[[Nanjing Massacre]]\n|1937, December 13\n|[[Nanjing]]\n|{{nts|110000}}<ref>Geometric mean of 40 and 300 thousand rounded to nearest 10 thousand.</ref>\n| 40,000\u2013300,000 deaths.The death toll is disputed, ranging from some Japanese claims of several hundred,<ref>[[Masaaki Tanaka]] claims that very few citizens were killed, and that the massacre is in fact a fabrication in his book ''[http://www.ne.jp/asahi/unko/tamezou/nankin/whatreally/ \u201cNankin gyakusatsu\u201d no kyok\u014d] (The \"Nanking Massacre\" as Fabrication)''.</ref> to the Chinese claim of a non-combatant death toll of 300,000.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2001/0820/p1s3-woap.html \"Why the past still separates China and Japan\"] Robert Marquand (August 20, 2001) Christian Science Monitor. States an estimate of 300,000 dead.</ref> Most other nations believe the death toll to be between 150,000\u2013300,000, based on the [[Nanjing War Crimes Tribunal]] verdict.\n|-\n|[[Changjiao massacre]]\n|1943, May 9\u201312\n|[[Changjiao]], [[Hunan]]\n|{{ntsh|30000}}30,000\n|\n|-\n|[[February 28 incident]]\n|1947, February 28\u2013May 16\n|[[Taiwan Province|Taiwan]]\n|5,000 to 28,000\n|Beginning of the [[White Terror (Taiwan)|White Terror]] campaign. The Chinese Kuomintang-led government imposed [[Martial law in Taiwan|martial law]] until 1987.\n|}\n\n== People's Republic of China (since 1949) ==\n\n=== 1949\u20131966 ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Chinese Land Reform]]\n|1948-1951\n|Nationwide\n|1,000,000 \u2013 4,500,000\n|Liquidation of the landlord class in [[struggle sessions]].\n|-\n|[[Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries]]\n|1950\u20131951\n|Nationwide\n|{{nts|1200000}}<ref>Geometric mean 712,000 and 2 million rounded to nearest 100 thousand.</ref>\n|712,000<ref name=\"Yang Kuisong\">{{cite journal|author=[[Yang Kuisong]]|year=2008|title=Reconsidering the Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=1809176|journal=[[The China Quarterly]]|volume=193|pages=102\u2013121|doi=10.1017/S0305741008000064}}{{paywall}}[https://chinachange.org/2011/11/28/reconsidering-the-campaign-to-suppress-counterrevolutionaries/ summary] at China Change blog</ref> to 2,000,000<ref name=\"Mao's Killing Quotas\">{{cite web|url=http://hrichina.org/public/PDFs/CRF.4.2005/CRF-2005-4_Quota.pdf|title=Mao's \"Killing Quotas.\" Human Rights in China (HRIC). 26 September 2005, at Shandong University|last=Changyu|first=Li|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090729194758/http://www.hrichina.org/public/PDFs/CRF.4.2005/CRF-2005-4_Quota.pdf|archivedate=29 July 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns]]\n|1951-1952\n|Nationwide\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Anti-Rightist Campaign]]\n|1957\n|Nationwide\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Socialist Education Movement]]\n|1963\n|Nationwide\n|77,560<ref>{{Cite book|last=Yang|first=Jishen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4d4qDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT67&lpg=PT67&dq=%E5%9B%9B%E6%B8%85%E8%BF%90%E5%8A%A8+77560&source=bl&ots=225yUBw_7e&sig=ACfU3U0ulCZv1-yRXfQDGSL6XMBILQ8aDw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjZy5-opK3nAhWAl3IEHeEpAF0Q6AEwAHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%E5%9B%9B%E6%B8%85%E8%BF%90%E5%8A%A8%2077560&f=false|title=\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986: \u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d\u5386\u53f2|date=2017-07-04|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=zh}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n=== 1966\u20131976 (Cultural Revolution massacres) ===\nSome of the massacres may have occurred during the [[Violent Struggle|Violent Struggles]] (300,000-500,000 deaths), [[Struggle session|struggle sessions]] or political purges.\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Red August]]\n|August \u2013 September 1966\n|[[Beijing]]\n|1,772<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phillips|first=Tom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/11/the-cultural-revolution-50-years-on-all-you-need-to-know-about-chinas-political-convulsion|title=The Cultural Revolution: all you need to know about China's political convulsion|date=2016-05-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n| The origin of the [[Red Terror]] of the [[Chinese cultural revolution|Chinese Cultural Revolution]]. Statistics from 1985 shows a death toll of over 10,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2011/09/201109160825.shtml|title=\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u201c\u975e\u6b63\u5e38\u6b7b\u4ea1\u201d\u4e86\u591a\u5c11\u4eba\uff1f ---- \u8bfb\u82cf\u626c\u7684\u300a\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u4e2d\u56fd\u519c\u6751\u7684\u96c6\u4f53\u5c60\u6740\u300b/\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last=Song|first=Yongyi|date=|website=Boxun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Guangxi Massacre]]\n|1966\u20131976\n|[[Guangxi]]\n|100,000 \u2013 150,000<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/china-cultrev-04292016134149.html|title=Interview: 'People Were Eaten by The Revolutionary Masses'|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhcqw.com/34/8938.html|title=\u6211\u53c2\u4e0e\u5904\u7406\u5e7f\u897f\u6587\u9769\u9057\u7559\u95ee\u9898|last=Yan|first=Lebin|date=|website=www.yhcqw.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|Cultural Revolution. Massive [[cannibalism]] occurred.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Inner Mongolia incident]]\n|1967\u20131969\n|[[Inner Mongolia]]\n|16,632 \u2013 100,000<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-mass-killings-during-chinese-cultural-revolution-1966-1976|title=Chronology of Mass Killings during the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|website=www.sciencespo.fr|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n|Cultural Revolution. Mostly [[mongols]].\n|-\n|[[Daoxian massacre]]\n|August \u2013 October\n1967\n|[[Daoxian]], [[Hunan]]\n|9,093<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Tan|first=Hecheng|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0QCDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=daoxian+massacre+7696&source=bl&ots=Ey81-ulNEi&sig=ACfU3U39emLWIUg0Al0ZiaFZ9WpMEccUQw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjA45jT8Z_mAhXvFjQIHSPFC4cQ6AEwBnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=daoxian%20massacre%207696&f=false|title=The Killing Wind: A Chinese County's Descent Into Madness During the Cultural Revolution|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-062252-7|language=en}}</ref>\n|Cultural Revolution.\n|-\n|[[Shaoyang County Massacre]]\n|July \u2013 September \n1968\n|[[Shaoyang County|Shaoyang,]]\n[[Shaoyang County|Hunan]]\n|991<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.modernchinastudies.org/us/issues/past-issues/105-mcs-2009-issue-3/1104-2012-01-05-15-35-41.html|title=\u201c\u6587\u9769\u201d\u65f6\u671f\u6e56\u5357\u7701\u90b5\u9633\u53bf\u201c\u9ed1\u6740\u98ce\u201d\u4e8b\u4ef6\u59cb\u672b|author=Lin|first=Qishan|date=|work=Modern China Studies|publisher=|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|Cultural Revolution. \n|-\n|[[Zhao Jianmin Spy Case]]\n|1968\u20131969\n|[[Yunnan]]\n|17,000<ref name=\":2\" />\n|Cultural Revolution.\n|-\n|[[Shadian incident|Shadian Incident]]\n|July \u2013 August\n1975\n|Yunnan\n|1,600<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zhou|first=Yongming|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8Rv-MsA4UGIC&pg=PA162&lpg=PA162&dq=shadian+incident&source=bl&ots=OZuKuX2tMC&sig=ACfU3U1BOCT7p37Nct-X_0PH1TfPMox9wQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6iYLnnNXmAhVJZc0KHa9lBCQQ6AEwCXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=shadian%20incident&f=false|title=Anti-drug Crusades in Twentieth-century China: Nationalism, History, and State Building|date=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-8476-9598-0|language=en}}</ref>\n|Cultural Revolution. Mostly [[Hui people]].\n|}\n\n=== 1976\u20131999 ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]]\n|1989, June 4\n|[[Tiananmen Square]], Beijing\n|{{ntsh|241}}1,000-10,000\n|Between 241 and 10,000 civilians were killed. [[International Committee of the Red Cross|The Red Cross]] states that around 2,600 died and the official Chinese government figure is 241 dead with 7,000 wounded.{{sfn|Zhang|2001|p=436}} {{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}[[Amnesty International]]'s estimates puts the number of deaths at several hundred to close to 1,000. [[NATO]] intelligence reported around 7,000 and the [[Soviet Union]] reported around 10,000.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} As many as 10,000 estimated people were arrested during the protests.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n|-\n|[[Thousand Island Lake incident|Thousand Island Lake robbery killings]]\n|1994, March 31\n|[[Zhejiang Province]]\n|{{ntsh|32}}32\n|24 Taiwanese tourists, 6 crew members, and 2 mainland Chinese passengers on board the \"Hai Rui\" sightseeing cruise were robbed and murdered. The incident cast a shadow over cross-strait relations.<ref>[http://news.hexun.com/2008-04-25/105559139.html \u7b2c67\u671f\uff1a\u5343\u5c9b\u6e56\u4e8b\u4ef6(\u7ec4\u56fe), (April 25, 2008)]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ghulja Incident]]\n|1997, February 5\n|[[Ghulja]], [[Xinjiang]]\n|{{ntsh|9}}9\n|Demonstrations in Ghulja were violently put down by police after two days of protesting. Official reports put the death toll at 9.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/50936.stm|title=China Uighurs executed|date=1998-01-27|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|Long wins round robbery\n|1998 November 15\n|[[Shanwei]]\n|{{ntsh|23}}23\n|Guangdong Province, Shanwei City, the territory of an armed robbery case, the Hong Kong shipping company \"Changsheng\" million tons of cargo ship on which 23 Chinese expatriate crew were all killed and their corpses dumped into the sea.<ref>[http://news.sohu.com/00/52/news201825200.shtml \u957f\u80dc\u8f6e23\u4eba\u60e8\u6848\u4e00\u4e3b\u72af\u843d\u7f51 \u5927\u6d77\u76d7\u5f20\u519b\u7ea2\u5373\u5c06\u53d7\u5ba1, (June 24, 2002)]</ref>\n|}\n\n=== 2000\u2013 ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[2014 Kunming attack|Kunming massacre]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/10675219/Kunming-massacre-Has-the-global-jihad-reached-China.html|title=Kunming massacre: Has the global jihad reached China?|newspaper=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en}}</ref>\n|2014, March 1\n|[[Kunming]]\n|{{ntsh|33}}33 (including four perpetrators)\n|\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n* [[Great Chinese Famine|Great Chinese famine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-mass-killings-during-chinese-cultural-revolution-1966-1976 \"Chronology of Mass Killings during the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976)\"] by Song Yongyi\n\n{{Massacres}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of massacres by country|China]]\n[[Category:China history-related lists|Massacres]]\n[[Category:Massacres in China|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}The following is a list of [[massacre]]s that have occurred in China. The massacres are grouped for different periods. \n\n== Imperial China (before 1912) ==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n|-\n! style=\"width:120px;\" |Name\n! style=\"width:65px;\" |Date\n! style=\"width:120px;\" |Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\" |Deaths\n! class=\"un