r, a high latitude particle spectrometer, an aerosol monitor, and an X-ray monitor<ref name=\"NASA P78-1\" />\n<!--orbit parameters-->\n| orbit_reference       = [[Sun-synchronous]]<ref name=\"NASA P78-1\">{{cite web|title=The P78-1 Satellite|url=http://heasarc.nasa.gov/docs/heasarc/missions/p78-1.html|publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center|accessdate=March 20, 2014|date=June 26, 2003}}</ref>\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_semimajor       = <!--semimajor axis-->\n| orbit_eccentricity    = .0022038<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_periapsis       = {{convert|515|km|mi}}<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_apoapsis        = {{convert|545|km|mi}}<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_inclination     = 97.6346\u00b0<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_period          = <!--time taken to complete an orbit-->\n| orbit_RAAN            = 182.5017<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_arg_periapsis   = 99.6346<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_mean_anomaly    = 260.9644<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_mean_motion     = 15.11755304<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_repeat          = <!--repeat interval/revisit time-->\n| orbit_velocity        = <!--speed at which the spacecraft was traveling at epoch \u2013 only use for spacecraft with low orbital eccentricity-->\n| orbit_epoch           = 1985 09 13.72413718<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_rev_number      = <!--revolution number-->\n| apsis                 = gee<!--planet specific apsis term (eg. gee/helion/selene/etc \u2013 defaults to generic \"apsis\")-->\n}}\n\n'''P78-1''' or '''Solwind''' was a [[United States]] [[satellite]] launched aboard an [[Atlas E/F|Atlas F rocket]] from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base]] in [[California]] on February 24, 1979. The satellite operated until it was destroyed in orbit on September 13, 1985 to test the [[ASM-135 ASAT]] anti-satellite missile.\n\n== Construction and payload ==\nThe satellite's [[Orbiting Solar Observatory]] (OSO) platform included a solar-oriented sail and a rotating wheel section. [[Ball Aerospace]] was the primary contractor for design and construction, and provided the [[attitude control]] and determination computer programs.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070612043842/http://www.robins.ball.com/p78.html Space Test Program P78-1 at Ball Aerospace]</ref> The P78-1 carried a [[gamma-ray]] [[spectrometer]], a white-light [[coronagraph]], an extreme-[[ultraviolet]] imager, an [[X-ray]] [[spectrometer]], a high-latitude particle spectrometer, an [[aerosol]] monitor, and an [[X-ray]] monitor. The X-ray monitor, designated NRL-608 or XMON, was a collaboration between the [[Naval Research Laboratory]] and [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]]. The white-light [[coronagraph]] and the ultraviolet imager were combined in a single package, designated NRL-401 or SOLWIND, which was built by the [[Naval Research Laboratory]].  The coronagraph was the flight spare of the white-light coronagraph on the [[OSO-7]] satellite.  The ultraviolet imager used a [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] imager, one of the first uses of a CCD in space.\n\n== Discovery of comets ==\n\nP78-1 was the first satellite in space to discover a comet in general and a [[sungrazing comet]] in particular. In total, 9 sungrazing comets, all belonging to the [[Kreutz Sungrazers|Kreutz group]], were discovered on images taken by the Solwind coronagraph:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Designation !! Discovery date !! Discoverer<ref>[http://cometography.com/sungrazers/sungrazersol.html Gary W. Kronk's Cometography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719213237/http://cometography.com/sungrazers/sungrazersol.html |date=2015-07-19 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rkracht.de/solwind/ My Solwind Comets (by Rainer Kracht)]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Comet Howard\u2013Koomen\u2013Michels|C/1979 Q1 (SOLWIND)]]|||| R. Howard, N. Koomen and D. J. Michels\n|-\n|C/1981 B1 (SOLWIND)|||| D. J. Michels, N. Sheeley, O. Roberts, and F. Harlow\n|-\n|C/1981 O1 (SOLWIND)|||| D. J. Michels, R. Seal, R. Chaimson, and W. Funk\n|-\n|C/1981 V1 (SOLWIND)|||| D. J. Michels, R. Seal, R. Chaimson, and W. Funk\n|-\n|C/1981 W1 (SOLWIND)|| June 30, 2005|| Rainer Kracht\n|-\n|C/1983 N2 (SOLWIND)|| July 19, 2005|| Rainer Kracht\n|-\n|C/1983 S2 (SOLWIND)|||| R. Howard, M. Koomen, D. Michels, and N. Sheeley\n|-\n|C/1984 O2 (SOLWIND)|||| N. R. Sheeley, Jr., R. Howard, M. Koomen, and D. Michels\n|-\n|C/1984 Q1 (SOLWIND)|| July 22, 2005|| Rainer Kracht\n|}\n\nApart from these yet another comet C/1984 R1 (SOLWIND) was found by Rainer Kracht on 23 July 2005 in Solwind's images. Its [[perihelion distance]] of 0.1051 [[Astronomical unit|AU]] was at least ten times larger than that of the previously found true sungrazers.\n\n== Destruction ==\nBy 1985, the satellite's batteries were degrading. This caused more and more frequent \"under-voltage cutoffs\", a condition where the satellite detected a low main bus voltage and automatically shut down all non-vital systems. In addition, the last of the three tape recorders failed in the spring of 1985, so data collection could only occur while the spacecraft was in contact with a ground station.<ref name=gunter /> A normal contact lasted only about 15 minutes, so this was a serious impediment.  Special arrangements could be made to string several contacts together.  As a result of these failures, an ever-increasing amount of time and network resources were spent reconfiguring the satellite for normal operation. Data collection from the few remaining payloads was severely limited. Because of the additional burden on the [[Air Force Satellite Control Network]] (e.g., extra support and antenna time at the tracking stations), discussions were already underway to terminate the mission.\n\nThis led to the satellite being chosen as a test target for an [[ASM-135 ASAT]] anti-satellite missile. The mission was extended for several weeks solely to support the test. During this final phase, the satellite was often allowed to remain in the under-voltage condition for several days at a time.\n\nOn September 13, 1985, the satellite was destroyed in orbit at 2043 [[UTC]] at {{coord|35|N|126|W||display=inline}} with an altitude of {{convert|525|km|mi}}<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" /> by an ASM-135 ASAT launched from a [[US Air Force]] [[F-15 Eagle]] [[fighter aircraft]]. The test resulted in 285 cataloged pieces of [[space debris|orbital debris]]. 1 piece of debris remained in orbit to at least May 2004,<ref>{{cite book |url= http://orbitaldebris.jsc.nasa.gov/library/satellitefraghistory/13theditionofbreakupbook.pdf |title= History of On-Orbit Satellite Fragmentations |edition= 13th |publisher= NASA Orbital Debris Program Office |pages= 12, 136 |date= May 2004 }}</ref> but had deorbited by 2008.<ref name=\"NASA 2008\">{{cite book |url= http://orbitaldebris.jsc.nasa.gov/library/SatelliteFragHistory/TM-2008-214779.pdf |title= History of On-Orbit Satellite Fragmentations |edition= 14th |publisher= NASA Orbital Debris Program Office |pages= 15, 144 |date= May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe test outraged some scientists because although five of P78-1's instruments had failed at the time of the test, two instruments remained in operation, and the satellite was what one [[solar physics|solar]] [[physicist]] called \"the backbone of [[solar corona|coronal]] research through the last seven years\".<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Science News |date=Sep 28, 1985 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/ASAT+target+was+working+research+satellite.-a03952265 |title=ASAT target was working research satellite |first=Jonathan |last=Eberhart}} <!-- alternate URL: https://archive.is/20120709124052/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1200/is_v128/ai_3952265/ --><!--official (paywalled) URL: https://www.sciencenews.org/archive/asat-target-was-working-research-satellite --></ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:ASM-135 ASAT 5.jpg|F-15A ''Celestial Eagle'' launching the ASAT missile that destroyed the P78-1\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[2007 Chinese anti-satellite missile test]]\n* [[USA 193]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://heasarc.nasa.gov/docs/heasarc/missions/p78-1.html NASA page about the satellite]\n* [http://heasarc.nasa.gov/docs/heasarc/missions/biblio/p78-1_ads.html List of research papers based on P78-1 observations]\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20120719001503/http://www.af.mil/information/heritage/milestones.asp?dec=1970-1980&sd=01/01/1970&ed=12/31/1989 |date=July 19, 2012 |title=Air Force Link, Milestones Thursday, January 01, 1970 \u2013 Sunday, December 31, 1989}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090105073429/http://www.astronautix.com/craft/solwind.htm Encyclopedia Astronautica Solwind Page]\n\n{{Sun spacecraft}}\n\n{{Orbital launches in 1979}}\n\n[[Category:NASA space probes]]\n[[Category:Intentionally destroyed artificial satellites]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1979]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Solwind / P78-1\n| image                 = P78-1-Solarwind sat.gif\n| image_caption         = The P78-1\n| mission_type          = Solar physics\n| operator              = {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] Space Test Program<ref name=gunter>{{cite web|last=Krebs|first=Gunter|title=Solwind (P78-1)|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/solwind.htm|publisher=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=March 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| website               =\n| COSPAR_ID             = 1979-017A<ref name=satcat>{{cite web|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|title=SATCAT|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|publisher=Jonathan's Space Pages|accessdate=March 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| SATCAT                = 11278<ref name=satcat/>\n| mission_duration      = 6 years, 6 months, 20 days\n\n| spacecraft_bus        =\n| manufacturer          = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ball Aerospace]]\n| dry_mass              = {{convert|850|kg|lb}}\n| launch_mass           = {{convert|1331|kg|lb}}<ref name=astronautix>{{cite web|title=Solwind|url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/solwind.htm|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=March 20, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624105038/http://www.astronautix.com/craft/solwind.htm|archivedate=June 24, 2014}}</ref>\n| power                 =\n\n| launch_date           = {{start-date|February 24, 1979, 08:24:00|timezone=yes}}&nbsp;UTC<ref name=astronautix />\n| launch_rocket         = [[Atlas E/F|Atlas F]]\n| launch_site           = [[Vandenberg Air Force Base|Vandenberg]], [[Vandenberg AFB Space Launch Complex 3|SLC-3W]]<ref name=astronautix />\n| launch_contractor     =\n\n| disposal_type         = Destroyed by ASAT\n| decay_date            = {{end-date|September 13, 1985}}\n| decay_field           = Destroyed\n| instruments           = [[Gamma-ray spectrometer]], a white light spectrograph, an extreme ultraviolet spectrometer, a high latitude particle spectrometer, an aerosol monitor, and an X-ray monitor<ref name=\"NASA P78-1\" />\n<!--orbit parameters-->\n| orbit_reference       = [[Sun-synchronous]]<ref name=\"NASA P78-1\">{{cite web|title=The P78-1 Satellite|url=http://heasarc.nasa.gov/docs/heasarc/missions/p78-1.html|publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center|accessdate=March 20, 2014|date=June 26, 2003}}</ref>\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_semimajor       = <!--semimajor axis-->\n| orbit_eccentricity    = .0022038<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_periapsis       = {{convert|515|km|mi}}<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_apoapsis        = {{convert|545|km|mi}}<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_inclination     = 97.6346\u00b0<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_period          = <!--time taken to complete an orbit-->\n| orbit_RAAN            = 182.5017<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_arg_periapsis   = 99.6346<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_mean_anomaly    = 260.9644<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_mean_motion     = 15.11755304<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_repeat          = <!--repeat interval/revisit time-->\n| orbit_velocity        = <!--speed at which the spacecraft was traveling at epoch \u2013 only use for spacecraft with low orbital eccentricity-->\n| orbit_epoch           = 1985 09 13.72413718<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" />\n| orbit_rev_number      = <!--revolution number-->\n| apsis                 = gee<!--planet specific apsis term (eg. gee/helion/selene/etc \u2013 defaults to generic \"apsis\")-->\n}}\n\n'''P78-1''' or '''Solwind''' was a [[United States]] [[satellite]] launched aboard an [[Atlas E/F|Atlas F rocket]] from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base]] in [[California]] on February 24, 1979. The satellite operated until it was destroyed in orbit on September 13, 1985 to test the [[ASM-135 ASAT]] anti-satellite missile.\n\n== Construction and payload ==\nThe satellite's [[Orbiting Solar Observatory]] (OSO) platform included a solar-oriented sail and a rotating wheel section. [[Ball Aerospace]] was the primary contractor for design and construction, and provided the [[attitude control]] and determination computer programs.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070612043842/http://www.robins.ball.com/p78.html Space Test Program P78-1 at Ball Aerospace]</ref> The P78-1 carried a [[gamma-ray]] [[spectrometer]], a white-light [[coronagraph]], an extreme-[[ultraviolet]] imager, an [[X-ray]] [[spectrometer]], a high-latitude particle spectrometer, an [[aerosol]] monitor, and an [[X-ray]] monitor. The X-ray monitor, designated NRL-608 or XMON, was a collaboration between the [[Naval Research Laboratory]] and [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]]. The white-light [[coronagraph]] and the ultraviolet imager were combined in a single package, designated NRL-401 or SOLWIND, which was built by the [[Naval Research Laboratory]].  The coronagraph was the flight spare of the white-light coronagraph on the [[OSO-7]] satellite.  The ultraviolet imager used a [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] imager, one of the first uses of a CCD in space.\n\n== Discovery of comets ==\n\nP78-1 was the first satellite in space to discover a comet in general and a [[sungrazing comet]] in particular. In total, 9 sungrazing comets, all belonging to the [[Kreutz Sungrazers|Kreutz group]], were discovered on images taken by the Solwind coronagraph:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Designation !! Discovery date !! Discoverer<ref>[http://cometography.com/sungrazers/sungrazersol.html Gary W. Kronk's Cometography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719213237/http://cometography.com/sungrazers/sungrazersol.html |date=2015-07-19 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rkracht.de/solwind/ My Solwind Comets (by Rainer Kracht)]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Comet Howard\u2013Koomen\u2013Michels|C/1979 Q1 (SOLWIND)]]|||| R. Howard, N. Koomen and D. J. Michels\n|-\n|C/1981 B1 (SOLWIND)|||| D. J. Michels, N. Sheeley, O. Roberts, and F. Harlow\n|-\n|C/1981 O1 (SOLWIND)|||| D. J. Michels, R. Seal, R. Chaimson, and W. Funk\n|-\n|C/1981 V1 (SOLWIND)|||| D. J. Michels, R. Seal, R. Chaimson, and W. Funk\n|-\n|C/1981 W1 (SOLWIND)|| June 30, 2005|| Rainer Kracht\n|-\n|C/1983 N2 (SOLWIND)|| July 19, 2005|| Rainer Kracht\n|-\n|C/1983 S2 (SOLWIND)|||| R. Howard, M. Koomen, D. Michels, and N. Sheeley\n|-\n|C/1984 O2 (SOLWIND)|||| N. R. Sheeley, Jr., R. Howard, M. Koomen, and D. Michels\n|-\n|C/1984 Q1 (SOLWIND)|| July 22, 2005|| Rainer Kracht\n|}\n\nApart from these yet another comet C/1984 R1 (SOLWIND) was found by Rainer Kracht on 23 July 2005 in Solwind's images. Its [[perihelion distance]] of 0.1051 [[Astronomical unit|AU]] was at least ten times larger than that of the previously found true sungrazers.\n\n== Destruction ==\nBy 1985, the satellite's batteries were degrading. This caused more and more frequent \"under-voltage cutoffs\", a condition where the satellite detected a low main bus voltage and automatically shut down all non-vital systems. In addition, the last of the three tape recorders failed in the spring of 1985, so data collection could only occur while the spacecraft was in contact with a ground station.<ref name=gunter /> A normal contact lasted only about 15 minutes, so this was a serious impediment.  Special arrangements could be made to string several contacts together.  As a result of these failures, an ever-increasing amount of time and network resources were spent reconfiguring the satellite for normal operation. Data collection from the few remaining payloads was severely limited. Because of the additional burden on the [[Air Force Satellite Control Network]] (e.g., extra support and antenna time at the tracking stations), discussions were already underway to terminate the mission.\n\nThis led to the satellite being chosen as a test target for an [[ASM-135 ASAT]] anti-satellite missile. The mission was extended for several weeks solely to support the test. During this final phase, the satellite was often allowed to remain in the under-voltage condition for several days at a time.\n\nOn September 13, 1985, the satellite was destroyed in orbit at 2043 [[UTC]] at {{coord|35|N|126|W||display=inline}} with an altitude of {{convert|525|km|mi}}<ref name=\"NASA 2008\" /> by an ASM-135 ASAT launched from a [[US Air Force]] [[F-15 Eagle]] [[fighter aircraft]]. The test resulted in 285 cataloged pieces of [[space debris|orbital debris]]. 1 piece of debris remained in orbit to at least May 2004,<ref>{{cite book |url= http://orbitaldebris.jsc.nasa.gov/library/satellitefraghistory/13theditionofbreakupbook.pdf |title= History of On-Orbit Satellite Fragmentations |edition= 13th |publisher= NASA Orbital Debris Program Office |pages= 12, 136 |date= May 2004 }}</ref> but had deorbited by 2008.<ref name=\"NASA 2008\">{{cite book |url= http://orbitaldebris.jsc.nasa.gov/library/SatelliteFragHistory/TM-2008-214779.pdf |title= History of On-Orbit Satellite Fragmentations |edition= 14th |publisher= NASA Orbital Debris Program Office |pages= 15, 144 |date= May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe test outraged some scientists because although five of P78-1's instruments had failed at the time of the test, two instruments remained in operation, and the satellite was what one [[solar physics|solar]] [[physicist]] called \"the backbone of [[corona]]l research through the last seven years\".<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Science News |date=Sep 28, 1985 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/ASAT+target+was+working+research+satellite.-a03952265 |title=ASAT target was working research satellite |first=Jonathan |last=Eberhart}} <!-- alternate URL: https://archive.is/20120709124052/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1200/is_v128/ai_3952265/ --><!--official (paywalled) URL: https://www.sciencenews.org/archive/asat-target-was-working-research-satellite --></ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:ASM-135 ASAT 5.jpg|F-15A ''Celestial Eagle'' launching the ASAT missile that destroyed the P78-1\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[2007 Chinese anti-satellite missile test]]\n* [[USA 193]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://heasarc.nasa.gov/docs/heasarc/missions/p78-1.html NASA page about the satellite]\n* [http://heasarc.nasa.gov/docs/heasarc/missions/biblio/p78-1_ads.html List of research papers based on P78-1 observations]\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20120719001503/http://www.af.mil/information/heritage/milestones.asp?dec=1970-1980&sd=01/01/1970&ed=12/31/1989 |date=July 19, 2012 |title=Air Force Link, Milestones Thursday, January 01, 1970 \u2013 Sunday, December 31, 1989}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090105073429/http://www.astronautix.com/craft/solwind.htm Encyclopedia Astronautica Solwind Page]\n\n{{Sun spacecraft}}\n\n{{Orbital launches in 1979}}\n\n[[Category:NASA space probes]]\n[[Category:Intentionally destroyed artificial satellites]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1979]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDestruction:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//